entry.title: Reland "Metrics Logging - Enable Network Time Tracker"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit f13743d651fc40015d1be01dd0e66a33192d82fc



There have been no changes from the original submission.



Now that a change to refactor the build files has landed [1], this should be safe to re-submit. The problem with the build files was that this change ended up bringing the whole network service (a large component) into the installer code, which doesn't need it. (It got there because the installer depends on the whole metrics component.) The build file refactoring makes the installer depend on a small part of the metrics component, which means the network service should't be dragged into the installer anymore.



[1] https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/f28351ae7fb4ac62e9267f7bc55a2f90dfec5509





Original change's description:

> Metrics Logging - Enable Network Time Tracker

>

> The framework to use network time tracker in metrics logging was landed

> in a disabled form in

> https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/3032615/

> At that time, compiling in network time tracker caused errors on

> certain Android bots. These errors came from a library brought in

> through transitive includes from webm. Those errors in webm have

> now been cleaned up.

>

> In the process of enabling the network time tracker, fix a bug exposed by tests:

>

> The creation of NetworkTimeTracker in BrowserProcessImpl::PreMainMessageLoopRun() was guarded by the feature flag network_time::kNetworkTimeServiceQuerying. This guard didn't do much, as a NetworkTimeTracker would be created automatically the first time it was accessed. (This use was unguarded.) This change removes the guard.

>

> (I considered applying the guard consistently everywhere, but it seems many tests rely on having an existing NetworkTimeTracker, even one that doesn't run queries for remote times. Removing the guard is the simplest way to keep the status quo. If someone wants later to guard all creations and fix all the test assumptions, that can be done elsewhere.)

entry.title: Refactor DelayHandler
entry.content:
This CL makes DelayHandler inherit directly from AudioHandler instead

of AudioBasicProcessorHandler.



This CL should cause no functional change.



This CL is in preparation for solving a spec compliance problem, but

does *not* solve the spec compliance problem. It is just a refactor.



The spec problem is as follows: the WebAudio spec requires that when the

channel count changes, we keep the audio data in the delay lines and

upmix or downmix it:

https://webaudio.github.io/web-audio-api/#DelayNode

However, the DelayHandler class inherits from

AudioBasicProcessorHandler, which will always destroy and recreate

the processing kernels whenever the channel count changes. This

discards the delay line state.



Bug: 1137007

entry.title: [Camera Roll] Throttle clicks on images to prevent duplicate downloads
entry.content:
This change uses a timestamp on camera roll thumbnails to prevent

them from being downloaded multiple times by accident via double-clicks,

etc. When requesting a download, a check to determine if more than 2

seconds (configurable by |ash_features| has passed since the last

download. If not, the download is not requested. In the base case,

TimeTicks has a timestamp of 0, so it won't block initial downloads.



Video Demo:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/17BJZ_6IPX7HnAfpgxjKf4-l3JVGazdIF/view?usp=drive_link&resourcekey=0-QRlRY5wO2Zfqx2zwYCZChA



Test: Manually verified that you cannot download a photo multiple times

until 2 seconds have passed. You can still download other photos, but

they each have their own timestamp. Once two seconds pass you can

download again. Closing and Re-opening Phone Hub will still respect the

throttle. Video demo provided, new unit tests added.

entry.title: Handle clipped overflow correctly in table fragmentation.
entry.content:
When we reach the end of a fragmentable node that clips its overflow,

children do not contribute to additional fragmentainers past that point.

See kDisableFragmentation in NGBreakStatus and

RelayoutWithoutFragmentation() in NGLayoutAlgorithm for details.



The table code didn't handle this correctly. Use

InvolvedInBlockFragmentation() instead of checking if block

fragmentation is active, so that we also handle cases where there's an

incoming break token, but no more fragmentation is to take place.



Table captions need to be re-laid out when we're re-laying out without

fragmentation, so that we resume at the break tokens, instead of

starting from scratch.

entry.title: [QT] Ensure QT platform matches Ozone platform
entry.content:
The only behavior change of this CL occurs when Chrome is running under

XWayland. Previously, QT would be initialized with the wayland backend,

but this CL changes QT to initialize with the xcb backend.



While we don't use QT for any native windowing, certain settings may

still differ depending on the platform. In particular, in KDE Wayland

when the "Legacy Applications (X11)" setting is set to "Scaled by the

system" instead of "Scaled by the application", QT will report a scale

factor of 1.0 on the xcb backend which may differ from the scale factor

reported on the wayland backend. This results in double scaling as

both Chrome and KDE apply the scale factor. The solution is to ensure

the QT platform matches the Ozone platform.

entry.title: Don't miss cache for orthogonal flow ancestor on subsequent layout.
entry.content:
If a node has already been laid out at least once in the current

lifecycle update, there's no need to miss the layout cache just because

there's an orthogonal writing mode root somewhere in there, since the

engine has had an opportunity to update things based on the new

containing block size.



For flex layout, missing the cache every time caused problematic

performance complexity (didn't check, but possibly O(2^n), 'n' being the

nesting level).



The performance test included is about 25000 times faster than before,

from about 0.065 runs per second, to about 1600 times per second (when

testing locally).

Original change's description:

> [Mac] Implement App Nap behaviour for background renderers

>

> With App Nap, sleeping processes are blocked from using too much of

> the system's resources. Under the hood, this is achieved by applying

> a suppression policy to the processes.

>

> With this change, background renderers will have that same suppression

> policy applied to them, which should have a significant effect on the

> performance of other processes.

>

> Another consequence of App Nap is that the OS gives that process a

> default task role of TASK_FOREGROUND_APPLICATION, and its QoS

> settings are set to tier 0.

>

> Thus this CL also updates the `SetCurrentTaskDefaultRole` function to

> apply the same default values to each child process. (The browser

> process already has those settings applied by the OS).

>

> This change only affect MacOS.

entry.title: [Feature Engagement] Move to configuration provider model.
entry.content:
This change moves local and field trial configuration out of chrome_variations_configuration.cc and into individual ConfigurationProviders.



This CL adds:

- FieldTrialConfigurationProvider, which reads from flag data,

either from the command line, Finch, or

fieldtrial_testing_config.json

- LocalConfigurationProvider, which replaces the old

feature_configurations.cc and group_configurations.cc files and

contains hard-coded configurations.



It should not actually change existing behavior, and all tests are left as-is as a result. (One minor change is that field trials may be parsed before checked-in configurations but valid trial data already prevented checked-in configuration, so the net behavior is the same.)



This is necessary because the Chrome Desktop User Education system will itself be a configuration provider in the future, and needs the ability to potentially override or fill in data.



See go/desktop-user-education-2.0 for details.



The TL;DR is that since there are mandatory default behaviors for IPH and "New" Badge, teams should not have to create a separate Feature Engagement configuration for these experiences; it should be handled by the User Education system.

entry.title: AbortSignal: Add null check in addEventListener's abort algorithm
entry.content:
The addEventListener abort algorithm uses a lambda whose first argument

is a WeakPersistent(event target), so unlike using a callback with a

weak receiver, the callback runs if the event target has been GCed.

This CL fixes this by adding a null check in the callback.



The crash is dependent on GC timing: the event target keeps the listener

alive, which keeps the abort handle alive, which makes the callback

eligible to run. If the event target has been GCed but the handle hasn't

yet, then the crash can happen.

entry.title: AbortSignal: Deflake memory tests
entry.content:
The abort signal memory tests rely on a single synchronous gc() to

collect signals and trigger finalization registry callbacks, which has

become flaky on Mac (worker tests only). The implementation was changed

recently, but the tests were reliably passing from 8/10 -- 8/16. The

change to use a per-Worker microtask queue in crrev.com/c/4781406 may

have caused the tests to start flaking (timing lines up, reverting it

locally fixes things), but it's not clear how that's affecting GC.



Testing on a Mac locally I found the third test fails fairly reliably, but attempts to debug it (heap snapshots w/ GC removed, console logs, tracing, etc.) removed the flakiness. Adding a second gc() reliably

fixes the third test, but other tests still fail (less often).



This CL refactors the tests to speculatively fix the flakes:

1. Run GC asynchronously. It's possible something on the stack is

holding onto the signal. This probably needs to be done anyways for

conservative stack scanning (other tests have been similarly

refactored to use.

2. Because of (1), change tests to use WeakRef instead of finalization

registry. This is cleaner and will fail before the timeout, giving

more insight into failures.

3. Do multiple rounds of gc. I found doing gc() multiple times fixed

test 3, but that could have also just changed timing. But blink

unit tests run GC in a loop, so it seems reasonable to do this to

ensure collection occurs in case multiple cycles are needed.



Locally on mac, the memory tests pass with these changes with

--repeat-each=1000, and I didn't find any flakes on the Mac bots.

entry.title: [EditContext] Handle replacement_range parameter in CommitText
entry.content:
WebInputMethodController::CommitText takes a replacement_range

parameter, where the expected behavior is that if the range is not

empty, the inserted text should be inserted at that position,

overwriting any existing text in that range.



EditContext::CommitText was ignoring that parameter. This was causing

issues with Mac long-press accent insertion (the menu that pops up

when holding down a certain keys where accents can be applied;

'a', 'n', etc). When the user selects an accent,

EditContext::CommitText is called to insert the new accented character

over the old one, so if the replacement_range is ignored then the

unaccented character is not removed.



In this CL, update EditContext::CommitText to use the parameter,

matching the corresponding behavior in SetComposition.

entry.title: [Extensions] CHECK that unspecified contexts can't make API calls
entry.content:
Javascript contexts in the renderer can sometimes be classified as

"unspecified" in rare cases. These should never have any APIs exposed

to them.



Add a renderer-side CHECK that they can't make API calls. We already

have browser-side checks that any API call comes from a context with

appropriate permission, but this is a nice-to-have check as well.
